@keis you can release to stable from https://dahsboard.snapcraft.io.

Or, install snapcraft with `sudo snap install snapcraft --classic`. It's spooky, because snapcraft needs to install packages in your machine in order to build stuff. In this case, the python interpreter. The project is free software, so you can always inspect that we are only executing what we say we will execute: https://github.com/snapcore/snapcraft/

And well, we are also the maintainers of the ubuntu archives, so if you are running Ubuntu you are already trusting your machines to us :) After 10 years of Ubuntu, I think we have proved to be reliable. But if you have any question, we are happy to answer anytime.

